It's probably a bad sign if you imagine an audience or following when you're writing; writing should be aimed at the individual, not a mob.
It never matters how "good" the mob is: "The will to a system is a lack of integrity."
Internet writing is awful for its knowing, familiar-yet-aggregating tone: it audience-ifies you as it elevates performative authors.
The war between writer and reader online reflects the fact that life is now a success if one is onstage, a failure if in the audience.
Not only is it preaching, not only do they act like priests, but they make you just another choir member, nameless and taking instructions.
Understand comments sections as a theater audience of the actors not chosen for the play offering their competing takes on the roles.
